{"amendments":[{"body":"`AgentExecutionService` no longer enforces the caller’s configured timeout for adapters that depend on the service-level guard. In `src/contexts/agent_execution/service.rs:196-221`, the timeout was changed from `request.timeout` to `request.timeout + 30s`, but adapters like the stub backend still only sleep/cancel cooperatively and do not apply their own hard deadline. That makes a 10ms request succeed after ~100ms instead of timing out; `tests/unit/agent_execution_test.rs:292-316` now fails under `cargo test --features test-stub --test unit agent_execution_test::service_times_out_and_requests_backend_cancellation`. This is a real regression in the timeout contract, not just a test issue.","rationale":"The change moved timeout enforcement out of the shared service path without updating the trait contract, so non-process backends can now overrun their configured deadlines."},{"body":"Exit-code classification still does not implement the requested fatal-path handling. `src/adapters/process_backend.rs:1452-1460` defines `classify_exit_failure`, but it ignores the `ExitStatus` and always returns `FailureClass::TransportFailure`; the call sites at `src/adapters/process_backend.rs:1282-1294` and `src/adapters/process_backend.rs:1304-1316` therefore retry exit 127 exactly like a transient transport failure. The new test at `tests/unit/process_backend_test.rs:2038-2068` even codifies this behavior, which contradicts the acceptance criterion that a missing binary / exit 127 should fail immediately without consuming the retry budget.","rationale":"This leaves one of the main hardening goals unimplemented: fatal backend setup failures are still treated as retryable flakiness."},{"body":"The new `BinaryNotFound` classification is dropped on some required availability-check paths, so those failures still retry as `TransportFailure`. In `src/contexts/workflow_composition/engine.rs:5954-5962` and `src/contexts/workflow_composition/engine.rs:6430-6446`, required prompt-review refiner / final-review planner / arbiter availability errors are rewrapped with `failure_class: None`. Because `AppError::failure_class()` defaults `BackendUnavailable { failure_class: None, .. }` to `TransportFailure` (`src/shared/error.rs:308-313`), a missing binary or missing API key from `check_availability()` becomes retryable again in those stages.","rationale":"Even if `ProcessBackendAdapter` returns a terminal `BinaryNotFound`, these wrappers erase it and reintroduce the same retry loop the task was meant to remove."}],"summary":"Reviewed the retry-hardening diff against `origin/master`, read the changed retry/timeout implementation paths, and exercised the impacted tests. I found three correctness issues: the shared service timeout contract regressed for non-process adapters, exit 127 is still treated as retryable, and some stage-availability wrappers erase the new terminal failure classification."}